Here is a conceptual outline of my scenario.

On the left of the screen, user can enter search criteria identifying list of customers (SearchOptions component).
Next to it is a grid (Customers component) that displays list of customers based on the search criteria specified in the SearchOptions component. Search results (Customers component) will be updated whenever user clicks "Search" button inside the SearchOptions component.
User can then click on an individual customer listed in the grid (Customers component) - at that point, both CustomerDetail and Document components needed to be updated to display additional information on the selected customer.

```
ViewCustomers Component (parent container)
----------------------------------------
|SearchOptions|Customers|CustomerDetail|
|  Name       |         |--------------|
|  Type       |         |Document      |
|--------------------------------------|
```
I am trying to understand what is the best practice to implement this scenario. First (and simplest approach) that I tried was to capture a callback from child components in the parent ViewCustomers component and then issue a call to referenced child components as necessary. According to the (very sparse) documentation, this seems to be an anti-pattern.

```
<div ...>
    <SearchOptions OnSearch="Search" />
</div>
<div ...>
    <Customers @ref="m_customers" OnSelectedCustomerChanged="SetCustomer" />
</div>
<div ...>
    <div ...>
        <div ...>
            <CustomerDetail @ref="m_customerDetail" />
        </div>
        <div ...>
            <Document @ref="m_document" />
        </div>
     </div>
</div>

@code
{
    protected Customers m_customers;
    protected CustomerDetail m_customerDetail;
    protected Document m_document;

    public void Search(SearchOptions options)
    {
        m_customers.Search(options);
    }

    public void SetCustomer(Guid customerGuid)
    {
        m_customerDetail.SetCustomerDetail(customerGuid);
        m_document.LoadDocument(customerGuid);
    }
}
```
Second approach that I tried (which based on researching the very little information there is on Blazor) was to create a service (ComponentState) that various components subsribe to. Individual component can then trigger an event to notify a parent/sibling component that the other component will then handle. Since I am storing model (such as Search or CustomerGuid) inside each inidvidual component, I am using the service only as a notification mechanism. Is this the right pattern?

One problem using this approach that I ran into is limited types of scopes when registering service. In my real-world project, there can be multiple instances of the parent ViewCustomers component (think Visual Studio-like multi-tab UI) and I need to inject instance of ComponentState that will only notify child components within that instance. I cannot use singleton for obvious reasons, so I ended up registering the service using transient scope and then pass the injected ComponentState instance into child components using <CascadingValue> parameter. Is this the right approach?

```
@inject ComponentState State

<CascadingValue Value="State" Name="ComponentState">
    <div ...>
        <SearchOptions />
    </div>
    <div ...>
        <Customer />
    </div>
    <div ...>
        <div ...>
            <div ...>
                <CustomerDetail />
            </div>
