### Describe the bug
When hosting an ASP.NET Core application using the IIS InProcess hosting model, if a X-Forwarded-Proto header is sent to the server it is not passed back to the ASP.NET Core application in either the `Request.Scheme` or the `Request.Headers` collection

### To Reproduce
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Using this version of ASP.NET Core 3.0.100 (also tested on 2.2.301)
2. Using the default Empty ASP.NET Core Web Application template use the following `Configure` method:

```
        public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
        {
            if (env.IsDevelopment())
            {
                app.UseDeveloperExceptionPage();
            }

            app.UseRouting();

            app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
            {
                endpoints.MapGet("/", async context =>
                {
                    string scheme = context.Request.Scheme;
                    var headers = new Dictionary<string, StringValues>(
                        context.Request.Headers
                            .OrderBy(h => h.Key));

                    context.Response.ContentType = "application/json";
                    await context.Response.WriteAsync(JsonSerializer.Serialize(new
                    {
                        Scheme = scheme,
                        Headers = headers
                    }));
                });
            });
        }
```
3. Deploy to IIS (in my case I'm deploying to Azure) using the default InProcess hosting model.
4. Send a request passing the value `http` in the `X-Forwarded-Proto` header:
```
curl -X GET https://<mywebsite>.azurewebsites.net/ -H 'X-Forwarded-Proto: http'
```
 and see the output:
```
{
	"Scheme": "https",
	"Headers": {
    // removing irrelevant headers
		"X-AppService-Proto": ["https"],
		"X-Forwarded-Proto": ["https"],
	}
}
```
### Expected behavior
I would expect either the `Request.Headers` collection to contain a header with the name "X-Forwarded-Proto" and the value "http"

### Additional context
I've been able to work around this issue by using the Out-of-Process hosting model, but it seems very unintuitive that there is a difference in behavior between the two models and that the header that is sent to the server is completely lost.

### Describe the bug
A `JsonResult` response does not include the `Content-Length` header. This is hidden and I was unable to detect it in unit tests because it seems that something in the core library is setting this value on an `HttpResponseMessage`.

### To Reproduce
1. Using ASP.NET Core 2.1.3
2. Create a controller (this one is intended to serve as the `rootdomain.com/.well-known/microsoft-identity-association.json` file):
```
public class MicrosoftController : Controller
{
    private readonly MicrosoftApplicationIdentitySettings _apps;

    private static JsonSerializerSettings jsonSettings = new JsonSerializerSettings
    {
        ContractResolver = new CamelCasePropertyNamesContractResolver()
    };

    public MicrosoftController(MicrosoftApplicationIdentitySettings apps)
    {
        _apps = apps ?? throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(apps));
    }

    // https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/howto-configure-publisher-domain
    public JsonResultWithContentLength GetIdentityAssociation()
    {
        var result = Json(_apps, jsonSettings);

        // We want exactly "application/json" with no charset or Azure will reject the file. See https://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/61ef2463-c132-4246-8748-c3090e0deed0/publisher-domain-verification-fails-because-quotverification-of-publisher-domain-failed-error?forum=WindowsAzureAD
        result.ContentType = new MediaTypeHeaderValue("application/json").ToString();

        return result;
    }
}
```
3. Serve the endpoint
4. Using Postman, run a GET request on your endpoint and note that the header `Content-Length` is not included.
5. Run unit test:
```
[Fact]
public async Task RouteToMicrosoftIdentityAssociation()
{
    var response = await _client.GetAsync("/.well-known/microsoft-identity-association.json");
    var content = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    var contentType = response.Content.Headers.ContentType;

    // We want exactly "application/json" with no charset. See https://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/61ef2463-c132-4246-8748-c3090e0deed0/publisher-domain-verification-fails-because-quotverification-of-publisher-domain-failed-error?forum=WindowsAzureAD
    var expectedContentType = new MediaTypeHeaderValue("application/json");

    Assert.Equal(HttpStatusCode.OK, response.StatusCode);
    Assert.False(string.IsNullOrEmpty(content));
    Assert.Equal(expectedContentType, contentType);
    Assert.NotEqual(0, response.Content.Headers.ContentLength.GetValueOrDefault(0));
}
```
6. Note that the test passes even though the header was not included, as shown by Postman

### Expected behavior

The `Content-Length` header should be set on JSON responses.

### Additional context

I am using 2.1.3 at the moment so was able to workaround this by inheriting from `JsonResult` and `JsonResultExecutor` and adding the header, but this will not be possible in 3.x as the executor has been changed to internal.

The problem exists in 2.1.3 and 3.x.

The reason I even found this was because the Azure portal requires the Content-Length header in order to verify a publisher domain, which means that I won't be able to use the Microsoft libraries to work with a Microsoft product.

